title: Fix incorrect box offset computation in NMS op
body:
**Description**: 
The `boxes` tensor in NMS is of shape [batch_size, num_boxes, 4]. So we don't need to multiply by `num_classes` in order to compute box offset.

This was not captured by any test case, because to trigger an incorrect box offset computation, we need both batch_size > 1 and num_classes > 1 (didn't have such a test case). Even then, it takes a very specific combination of `iou_threshold`, `box coordinates`, and `box scores` to trigger an overall test case failure by selecting wrong boxes (hard to write a test case that fails without this change and succeeds (as expected) with this change).

**Motivation and Context**

title: MLAS: add U8U8 MatMul operation
body:
**Description**:
Implement the first round of changes for quantization inside MLAS. This adds a MatMul operation for U8xU8=S32 for x86/x64 processors.

**Motivation and Context**
This implements a version of U8xU8=S32 MatMul that works for SSE2/AVX2/AVX512BW/AVX512VNNI for Windows and Linux/OSX. The API is single-threaded in this iteration. This is enough to start plugging into the runtime in place of gemmlowp.

AVX1 systems could go faster by enhancing the existing SSE2 based kernel to use more registers, or implement SSE4.1 special case kernels, or go all the way and do AVX1 kernels. That can come later. x86 systems only have SSE2 kernels for now but could also implement AVX2 later if needed.

This change also implements the .hidden fix for the NCHWc assembly kernels to avoid reloc errors when using -fPIC and building Linux shared libraries. Several helpers were meant to be internal only and .hidden keeps them from showing up in the export table.

**Description**: 
Enables subbing in the mimalloc memory allocator for the default memory allocator (the flag --use_mimalloc is off by default though).

It's important to note why the Windows vs Linux/MacOS builds of mimalloc differ in the CMake changes below. While the mimalloc project does have a CMake project that builds on Windows, the mimalloc dll produced doesn't have the required hooks necessary to override malloc on Windows at runtime. title: Fix one possible crash in constant folding optimizer when session thread pool is in-use
body:
**Description**: 

Code like this won't work:

```C++
Status SomeKernel::Compute(OpKernelContext* ctx) const {
  auto ctx_internal = static_cast<OpKernelContextInternal*>(ctx); //this cast is unsafe. Itâ€™s from a base class to a derived class.
  concurrency::ThreadPool* tp = ctx_internal->GetOperatorThreadPool();
}
```
OpKernelContextInternal is inherited from OpKernelContext. But OpKernelContext is not an abstract class!
Therefore, sometimes, the pointer ctx, is not a OpKernelContextInternal

For example, in ConstantFolding,
```c++
auto* kernel = info.GetKernel(node->Index());
OpKernelContext op_kernel_context(&frame, kernel, ::onnxruntime::logging::LoggingManager::DefaultLogger());
ORT_RETURN_IF_ERROR(kernel->Compute(&op_kernel_context));
```
So, if the kernel was involved in ConstantFolding, then the program will crash. 

This is just a **partial** fix. This PR will attempt to solve the problem related to  GetOperatorThreadPool call.   But, there are some other places are also using "static_cast<OpKernelContextInternal*>". 

This PR also tries to fix some compiler warnings. 

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: MLAS: remove @PCGOTREL x64 usage
body:
**Description**:
Avoid the need for @PCGOTREL relocations by annotating MLAS global data shared with assembly modules with __attribute__(visibility("hidden")).

**Motivation and Context**
A few months ago, I changed the x64 kernels to use @PCGOTREL to access global data, which is required when building -fPIC and default symbol visibility. This comes at the cost of an extra instruction to read the data address. However, this wasn't needed if the global data symbol is marked as hidden. Doing this gets the x64 Linux code closer to the original x64 Windows code + also fixes issue #1703 where older versions of clang are not compiling @PCGOTREL properly.

title: MLAS: Android sgemm kernel build fix
body:
**Description**: 
Fix the aarch64 kernel to build properly with the Android NDK (specifically clang).

**Motivation and Context**
The Android build was falling back to the intrinsic based ARM version instead of using the aarch64 assembly kernel due to a build break. clang was properly complaining that the "uxtw" modifier should not be used with 64-bit wide registers, whereas gcc ignored the mismatch and treated it as the "lsl" modifier I had intended.

Also rename the ARM64 files to match the pattern used for amd64/x86_64. Also rename the aarch64 kernel to ".S" to invoke the preprocessor (same as x86_64) and avoid warnings about unused command line parameters.

Also remove x86 on ARM64 emulation support that was never used and only had value inside the Windows source tree.
